{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "We propose to extend standards to include the publication of: (i) a description of the modeling frameworks used to generate weights and cell-level predictions of preferences; (ii) for each model, an acceptable measure of 'variable importance'-a measure of which variables played a larger or smaller role relative to other inputs in the estimation of weights and preferences.",
    "This extended disclosure serves two purposes: First, (i) allows for general transparency with respect to methodology, via the description of the ML models employed in the poll.",
    "Here it is worth noting that a general level of detail for each chosen model would be sufficient for transparency purposes-for example, in the classic case of MrP with structured priors (Gao et al. 2021) it would be enough to know that this is the chosen method, rather than to explicate every subsequent modeling choice within this paradigm.",
    "This also allows pollsters to be transparent while not jeopardising the economic value of any novel intellectual property they might be experimenting with.",
    "Second, (ii) enables the public to scrutinise instances of 'bad learning', by having access to measures of variable importance for preference prediction and weighting."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
